  "description": "The Lambda-CDM model is the standard model of cosmology. It describes a universe that is spatially flat, governed by general relativity, and composed of approximately 5% baryonic matter, 27% cold dark matter (CDM), and 68% dark energy in the form of a cosmological constant (Lambda, Λ\\Lambda).\nThe model has six free parameters:\nΩbh2\\Omega_b h^2 \u0026ndash; baryon density Ωch2\\Omega_c h^2 \u0026ndash; cold dark matter density θ∗\\theta_* \u0026ndash; angular size of the sound horizon at recombination τ\\tau \u0026ndash; optical depth to reionization nsn_s \u0026ndash; scalar spectral index (tilt of the primordial fluctuation spectrum) AsA_s \u0026ndash; amplitude of primordial fluctuations These six numbers, combined with the Friedmann equations and the physics of the pre-recombination plasma, predict the angular power spectrum of the cosmic microwave background, the distribution of galaxies, the abundances of light elements, the expansion history, and the age of the universe. The predictions match observations across all these independent tests.\n",
  "name": "Lambda-CDM Model",
